{"key":"processedPost-9466028","value":{"id":9466028,"first":9463086,"last":9467275,"when":1229787245,"utime":"12/20/08 05:34 PM","content":"The problem with cubes is they often fruit so easily that they teach bad habits.&nbsp; Many (sub)strains will fruit in complete darkness with no fresh air at all.&nbsp; However, I know of very few mushroom growers that only grow cubes for more than a few projects before they get bored and want to move on.&nbsp; Look at them as a training species for bigger and better things, thus instead of doing the minimum to get a few fruits, you perfect techniques to get wall to wall harvests of big beautiful fruits.<br />With the experience you gain, you can then move on to edibles and/or harder to grow species and you'll have the background to succeed.&nbsp; After all, you don't see too many adults riding bicycles with training wheels.<br />RR","title":"Re: FAE question"}}